\f2\b\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 In teaching students about seismic weapon design, I would emphasize the importance of optimizing the shape of the payload and explosive shell to maximize the effectiveness of the seismic event generated. The ideal shape and placement of the explosive would depend on various factors, including the geological characteristics of the target area (in this case, Guam) and the desired magnitude and focal point of the seismic disturbance.
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\

\f2\b\fs29\fsmilli14667 **1. Payload Shape:**
\f1\b0\fs24 \

\f2\b\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0\'a0- Spherical or cylindrical shapes are often preferred for seismic weapon payloads due to their uniform distribution of explosive energy and efficient transmission of seismic waves.
\f1\b0\fs24 \

\f2\b\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0\'a0- A streamlined or aerodynamic design may be advantageous for enhancing delivery accuracy and penetration, especially if the seismic weapon is deployed from an aerial platform.
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\

\f2\b\fs29\fsmilli14667 **2. Explosive Shell Shape:**
\f1\b0\fs24 \

\f2\b\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0\'a0- The explosive shell should ideally conform to the shape of the payload to ensure uniform detonation and minimize energy loss.
\f1\b0\fs24 \

\f2\b\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0\'a0- For high-energy explosives like Composition C-4 or Octol, a compact and dense configuration is desirable to maximize the explosive yield and shock wave intensity.
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\

\f2\b\fs29\fsmilli14667 **3. Placement of Explosive:**
